author: pboothroyd96

description.text:
With this adapter you can transform your 3D printer into a CNC: it allows you to install a 300W engraving DC spindle (52mm dia) onto a base plate that has 50mm center-to-center M4 holes. These CNC spindles are common on eBay and typically come with an ER11 collet and weigh around 800 grams (a bit more than two extruders). The design might require modifications to fit your printer as I've built this originally for my Delta bot which is custom build and I did not have an opportunity to test on specific printer models, if you do and it works, please report back. Remember to limit the Z axis travel to fit the spindle. See also: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:296799 for a Dremel variant of this. Additional parts needed:
  • 3x 30mm M3 screws and nuts for clamping the spindle
  • 2x M4 screws with nuts - height will depend on your printer, typically 10-16mm
I printed mine out of PLA, with 0.2mm layer height and 50% infill. Seems to be plenty strong.

title: Rostock E3D Bowden tubed Fan Mounting

description.text:
This thing allows 3 squirrel cage blower fans (I used 5015S DC Blower) to be mounted to the carriage of a Rostock and blow into tubing aimed at the end of the nozzle.   
It is designed for bottom mounted E3D hotends.

Additional materials:
  • 3x 5015S DC Blower Fans
  • Approx 600mm of tubing. STLs are provided for 10mm OD clear tubing as seen in pictures.
  • Screws or cable ties for affixing the fans.
    • FOR BELOW MOUNTED E3D HOTENDS ONLY. ONLY TESTED WITH v4 E3D BUT SHOULD WORK WITH v5 TOO AFAIK.
  • Print the tabbed shroud and fan tube output.
  • Print 3x nozzles and 3x fan mounts.
  • Remove the E3D hotend, replace default shroud with
  • Mount the fans to the fan mounts then the fan mounts to the carriage.
  • Mount the fan tube output onto the tabs of the fan shroud.
  • Place tubing through the outputs in the tube ends, place a nozzle and then place into a fan. Cut tubing to size so it won't interfere with printing.

comments.text:
I would be a little concerned at all of the moving mass of three motors and fans. I have used something similar with very flexible silicone tubing from an aquarium pump https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4tM17pXZQlshttps://www.youtube.com/watch?...
Although this, along with a more recent true ring cooler do work, I don't know if all of that work justifies the small improvement over a lightweight fan.
comments.author: leadinglights

comments.text:
That setup looks really cool! I was worried since the tubing i could find near me was very stiff that it might have issues with such a long setup, plus I wasn't confident enough in my abilities to buy an expensive fan to mount far from the hotend.
The fans themselves are quite lightweight, and the airflow is MUCH MUCH more powerful than my previous setup http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:170317http://www.thingiverse.com/thi..., and I had problems with asymmetric artifacts on my prints due to the uneven cooling.

author: Adz85

description.text:
Neuroscience education can be promoted by the availability of low cost and engaging teaching materials. To address this issue, we developed an open-source lipid bilayer amplifier, the OpenPicoAmp, which is appropriate for use in introductory courses in biophysics or neurosciences dealing with the electrical properties of the cell membrane. The amplifier is designed using the common lithographic printed circuit board fabrication process and off-the-shelf electronic components. In addition, we propose a specific design for experimental chambers allowing the insertion of a commercially available polytetrafluoroethylene film. This experimental setup can be used in simple experiments in which students monitor the bilayer formation by capacitance measurement and record unitary currents produced by ionic channels like gramicidin A. Used in combination with a low-cost data acquisition board this system provides a complete solution for hands-on lessons, therefore improving the effectiveness in teaching basic neurosciences or biophysics. http://arxiv.org/abs/1403.7439
http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0108097
